document.title: Ohio’s Learning Standards – Extended with Learning Progressions Social Studies

DD594A1E21F54D8BB0E2517A6A8128AC.description: Match specific item to its cost.

72E5067FA6684E7CAA37A52E451CACBC.description:
Define budget as a plan of how to spend an estimated
income (money you earn) within a given amount of
time.

39417B14A08D4EDDB221B43EFD70CA88.description:
Match
specific items to
their estimated
cost.

2948875226454BDEAAB17E39D6FF8CD4.description:
Make a
choice of an item to
purchase that fits into
a budget.

4ED7B5671C6A41B9BB067EC7B44D58B6.description:
Identify
examples of
income (money
you make) and
expenses (what
you spend money
on).

B43478C769264D7B83A0C309A36CF051.description:
A budget is a plan to
help people make personal
economic decisions for the
present and future and to
become more financially
responsible.

0B6591B138874EC6A396FE528D426016.description: Engage in the efforts and benefits of a token economy.

BA7E243DC880469F992C3A0384821B12.description:
Identify the benefits of completing a task in the
classroom or school community.

2E5A086353FB4A8CB06F6F26F3494A28.description:
Discuss how a student decides whether to complete a task
by weighing costs and benefits.

63A82A83782942438CB0C2B5AA6CDBBD.description:
Identify
something a
person gets
as a result of
completing a job or
chore (e.g., money,
stickers, candy).

34B53E6CBEDE486483AF9DED31EFDB68.description:
Identify positive
consequences of
having a job.

B984600C9A2542EB856E21E0DBB7B838.description:
Identify negative
consequences of
not having a job.

C17756828C95464B95273E375CCB50FB.description:
Making decisions
involves weighing costs and
benefits.

A2D07CDBDFDF48FFA97AEB6B4657B971.description:
Engage with items that can be purchased at a
specific location.

DAF5628A05724768A5F218FAF3AF1B19.description:
Virtually or physically visit locations where specific
items can be purchased.

B0B0ADD45AC940AFB21D49C72026ADC1.description: Select items that are needed or wanted.

3B1E9CE31902454CA4984F3D297A27A6.description: Identify where a desired item could be purchased.

1B2CFE1F33594D638FFFEC81B21738B5.description:
Identify
places to buy
things in the
community (e.g.,
markets).

17D164F865434AFABEE9585CA90FC7A5.description:
Match
goods/services to
markets (e.g., gas to
a gas station, bread
to the grocery store,
haircut to a barber).

60E6785E44AB40F9BD608F479B4ED63F.description:
Describe
the different things
you can do in a
market (e.g., buy
products, ask
questions, look at
different products,
make returns).

DCACE69055FF4622988C5186962E574C.description:
A market is where
buyers and sellers exchange
goods and services.

3CA307C31FC1403B82DD8D6F4ECA9E7A.description:
Engage with representations of goods, such as a
notebook, crayons, that students use in the classroom.

5E2D29B5F51D491B8F1EF6CC1FC00E69.description:
Identify the people who provide goods and services in
the school, such as cafeteria staff, custodian.

1E23DFCB8E1D4C0A86A3154F187A38E0.description:
Match
goods or services
to the producer
(e.g., corn to a
farmer, bread to
a baker, mail to a
postmaster).

9E1083A8F78C4C60BAB9212FC3038AE2.description:
Identify
consumers for
products or services
(e.g., power plant
would be a consumer
of coal).

9CA34182845B4834806CFD1F7A623097.description:
Given
a product or
service, identify
both the producer
and potential
consumer (e.g.,
corn produced
by farmers and
consumed by
biofuels, grocery
retailers, animals).

51131CC385794F9AA161442B46C78CDE.description:
A consumer is
a person whose wants
are satisfied by using
goods and services. A
producer
makes goods and/or provides
services.

9764432B878844399884D7A9C558B77C.description:
Identify
what is gained
as the result of
a purchasing
decision.

F0D10B3B07AB40748A7462E4C5E0EF76.description:
Identify
what is gained as a
result of choosing not
to make a purchase.

F47A601EF4EF4A94BC5EFC79F2564E59.description:
Explain
the “opportunity
cost” when
choosing which
item or items to
purchase (e.g.,
Buy 3 of an item or
just 1 of an item).

73000C1563AB4A49AB9217CC4138DF7C.description:
Individuals must
make decisions because of
the scarcity of resources.
Making a decision involves a
trade-off.

ABF35DC3DBF44719BEB982C9896CD02F.description:
Engage with representations of positive outcomes in
place for the classroom or school-wide behavioral
supports system (e.g., certificate, sticker, chart, bulletin
board).

B8C429788B5F4532A56E5A241DCA819A.description:
Identify positive consequences (classroom rewards) that
are the result of a given behavior.

6B9B0ECC782A4EC4A251C6DEA8ABC0CA.description:
Identify negative consequences (classroom
disincentives) that are the result of a given behavior.

978CB0BA358243F0BB0214E6543C3CB6.description:
Identify a
positive or negative
outcome of a
choice or behavior.

7FF425289604492BA95FA00381001247.description:
Categorize
examples of positive
and negative
incentives that affect
a person’s choice.

D80F6A199E334F7CA1A86A5E83DC649E.description:
Compare positive
and negative
cause and effect of
a behavior (e.g.,
late library book
versus reward for
chore).

BF1A7AE7929149BA8E59D0424DA32269.description:
Both positive and
negative incentives affect
individuals’ choices and
behaviors.

F2C67D881F994354AD224B811B4C67F8.description:
Engage with line graphs and bar graphs by tracing
the shapes to notice their differences.

D5CEDD3C506C431DB538557DEF7B1D52.description: Sort sample graphs into “line graphs” and “bar graphs.”

E28EA34C400043B1B28F3887C01DD41F.description:
Use models of line graphs as a reference in data
discussion. (use a peg board showing simple
samples of line graphs showing a line angled up,
down, and even)

39BB8CDFB5964346A954E26B6711928F.description:
Recognize a line
graph and identify
one variable.

D9207541D6B84715A1803171BFFA1868.description:
Identify both
variables on a line
graph.

6AAD9F47190440C28CF8293337C14BE1.description:
Distinguish
between line
graphs that show
positive and
negative change
over time.

632BF9764DD14D95A2652EAC34CB5B38.description:
Line graphs are used
to show changes in data over
time.

D9CA0298848A42829429CEBD20EB1CE5.description:
Engage with leaders or representations of leaders
within the school community.

99982606828E4B54A35CD300155A81FF.description:
Understand that there are specific rules and leaders
in different settings.

CFB00CB7D4AE47EDB883B71DEBB7050A.description:
Match representations of specific settings with the
leaders in those settings.

D41CA1EBFE1D429F8D50AC2A02328E78.description:
Identify
one type of local
government
structure (e.g.,
municipal, county,
township, special).

513C67C55943480CA4D6C2CC347D7EDB.description:
Identify
two types of local
government structures
that are different (e.g.,
municipal, county,
township, special).

F5B6E5517B164E46B1AFD2EB4377F8A5.description:
Compare
two types of
local government
structures that
are different (e.g.,
municipal, county,
township, special).

33C37F01927B4E5D9055C5054EBFF9CD.description:
The structure of local
governments may differ from
one community to another.

8BAC292C81164D92BD037C3C56414974.description:
Engage with representations of people in the community
who have the authority to enforce laws.

883F8E4C72A042C586F11335DFD42308.description: Engage with a story of an authority figure enforcing a law.

4094C9BFA552479BB16767C5432AFFAC.description:
Describe the roles and responsibilities of leaders
in different settings.

54BF0D758C3D40C68175160C8C67F579.description:
Identify
a person in the
community who
has the authority to
enforce laws (e.g.,
game wardens,
police officers,
mayor, firefighters,
safety patrol).

D55DF3ED8DFD43B59FA68980CDA78915.description:
Describe
the ways rules are
enforced by authority
figures at a school
(e.g., teacher,
counselor, principal,
security officer)

48A2DB4302564246938FA7B168668D89.description:
Describe
the ways laws
are enforced
by authority
figures and
government (e.g.,
establish fines,
incarceration).

35963C6A76D846A19C797D7FBA217F9F.description:
Governments have
authority to make and enforce
laws.

DCF040F0B791431F80BB1E0007F45E85.description: Engage while rules or expectations are reviewed.

8A330BF770014DA19997B62CBF880C2A.description:
Understand what a rule is and how they help the
classroom community (safety, respect, rights,
order).

BD1C58D621264121845B5E93A71D124B.description:
When given a rule, demonstrate actions or behaviors
that meet the expectations.

72AF9F1152ED4D9BA211DDF8777057B5.description: Identify posted rules in a given location.

317E97FA56DD44FC82FD6B762EF46F05.description:
Identify
a rule and its
expectations.

A6606EE5D71641D7A809EE4D930A67CF.description:
Identify
a rule and why it
is important.

53008586845F43A3BFF0111267456CEE.description:
State a
law and explain
why it is important.

0E6D5A22FB834273AC426A84A2FFCA49.description:
Laws are rules
that apply to all people in
a community and describe
ways people are expected to
behave. Laws promote order
and security, provide public
services, and protect the
rights of individuals in the
local community.

307191E6F5ED43FEA3764D70D46585F6.description:
Engage with representations of community members
responsible for solving problems (e.g., firefighters,
police officers, custodians, veterinarian, etc.).

7DEE79C7B96B49609F58167821C5E7B8.description:
Match images of community members to images of
the problems they solve (e.g., firefighter and a fire).

378726DB311240899A0D4CC85B47345D.description:
Identify
individuals in the
community who
solve problems
(e.g., firefighter
puts out fires,
doctor helps the
ill).

274BA2D1F50A4B88B9016C53039AB43D.description:
Match
problems with action
pictures that promote
the common good.

BD114E55FC4947449BE038750AAA09DF.description:
Identify
a problem in the
community and
how you would
correct it.

E3B04D75836D43379D7659ED841A0266.description:
Individuals make
the community a better
place by taking action to
solve problems in a way that
promotes the common good.

3BAF3F3F4ECD41F68CF3B225DC8F212C.description:
Engage with representations of students
performing classroom or home chores.

748D8DE1414546F69CDB23AD0473E4B2.description:
Sort images of students in a classroom into examples
and non-examples of “responsible” (e.g., students leaving
a messy work area, students putting art supplies away).

DAE9305CC3254888939C4C501FBC540E.description:
Identify
responsibilities that
you have in your local
school community.

0DCC1E11C4D94D0EAEEEE6498D5F2384.description:
Describe
members of the
local community
and their
responsibilities.

6BEA2376947E4BC9958D141B808215BD.description:
Members of local
communities have rights and
responsibilities.

613D0FED9F394697A3CA7BDC8C588432.description:
Engage with manipulatives organized into two sets -
one set with all same characteristics and one set with
items having different characteristics.

66D9BD98F98C4DB89FBC2486D96D7A35.description:
Sort manipulatives into multiple sets (cultures) based on
“same” characteristics (color, size, or shape) to show
each group has something in common. Next, create a
large set of all items to show how a larger group
(community) can consist of items with “different”
characteristics.

930D1EE8D8FB4496B8051CCC093FF941.description:
Identify
ways that humans
are the same and
different in a local
community (e.g.,
family, classroom).

684E9CE086E044A4BE99BFA54B7EA5FD.description:
Describe
practices among
different cultural
groups within the local
community (e.g., food,
clothing, heritage,
religion).

16A6CBE0FDF74A74AC37CC316F47FA4D.description:
Compare
practices among
different cultural
groups (e.g.,
traditional foods,
clothing and
customs).

A0826F0E2A2C47F7AC2B18FD359F4055.description:
Communities may
include diverse cultural
groups.

FB871D946A7B48CCBC8AC816C43559C1.description:
Engage with models or toys of automobiles,
busses, airplanes, ships, trucks, trains, etc.

FF7957D61D6F4602AC61607999D857D3.description:
Sort models or toys into categories of “land,” “water,” and
“air” transportation.

2E4910EEE4CA423D8CF695B96A39E0AF.description:
Match
methods of
transportation with
what they typically
transport.

68A3D20FF85A477F986F7F2AE248A158.description:
Identify
different types
of transportation
for products and
people.

2A23CAE1249642B5972CF1D76CEAD5E9.description:
Systems of
transportation and
communication move people,
products and ideas from place
to place.

F3FBA271829B4FC2AD6DFD1E91719D72.description:
Engage with representations of earth movers (e.g., toy
bulldozers, dump trucks) to experience how humans
can change the physical landscape.

384C4A8209744221A25DDC1D93B80CD9.description:
Create or identify representations (e.g., drawing,
coloring, building blocks) of human changes or additions
to a field (e.g., housing, shopping center, sports fields).

C5587E9FD45A41848A09AF7E10CF8258.description:
Recognize a
human change to
the local
environment (e.g.,
farmland used for
a new subdivision,
damming a river to
create a lake).

BD52D003509343BEA2E234026CB20BBB.description:
Identify a
human change to the
local environment
and explain why it is
positive or negative.

3BF062B697FD49E7905E462C94BC8B44.description:
Describe
both a positive and
negative human
change to the local
environment.

246329E1727048718822FE2FD8ACCE9A.description:
Evidence of
positive and negative
human modification of the
environment can be observed
in the local community.

F83AD79940D146698A7FA8A01BAC4E0C.description:
Engage with representations or samples of
observable natural resources (e.g.., soil, water, trees,
rocks).

C9705B34EA0F4E8C95DC9BF73078D106.description:
Select from a given set images of products created
from trees.

62447A7CF957458D99997C9999AEEDAA.description:
Identify a
natural resource
(e.g., soil, water,
coal, oil).

4774C4F6CBD64F8194B23F8DE53BA42C.description:
Identify
the natural
resources in Ohio.

1D8B6C45C4714A1886F43D101C32B421.description:
Identify
different resources
in the local
community (e.g.,
natural, economic
[businesses that
create jobs], and
cultural [museums,
universities,
festivals]).

D80B98380BEA499A92F4F52B7E240F9D.description:
Daily life is influenced
in different communities by
their agriculture, industry,
and natural resources.

BD49D65F007A4809844ADF8AE17D7665.description:
Engage with the classroom emergency exit map by
traveling the route, or tracing the route on paper, to
the nearest emergency exit.

C8A74D5526E646D58E800BA1EB9226BA.description:
Identify familiar places on the classroom emergency
exit map.

728DABC527EE41949A1E5335F69689BB.description:
Identify a
symbol on a simple
map.

AA7CF31D3E784CE5AAAA94EECFB16A0F.description:
Use a map
and map tools (e.g.,
legend, alphanumeric
grid lines) to locate
familiar landmarks,
streets and other
features.

7AFB391175C34A2DB95B625FA7471A95.description:
Identify
north, south, east
and west on the
compass rose on a
map.

157B14B37E6B41E2828E531828B39D5C.description:
Physical and political
maps have distinctive
characteristics and purposes.
Places can be located on
a map by using the title,
key, alphanumeric grid,
and cardinal directions.

5179283E58CC4036890AD3B98A8FE168.description:
Engage with representations of local buildings (e.g.,
schools, stores, town hall, Main Street) from multiple
time periods.

82650326800D41FCA8F1A60F06209764.description:
Sort representations of local buildings into “then”
and “now,” noting differences.

FB5A51CB42D04332B02B7FADDDE2E315.description:
Identify
a change within a
local community.

5C335DE649D34BF5B7C712D808F9B29A.description:
Describe
changes in the local
community (e.g., new
stores, houses and
other construction).

F925A084DC544A53864C06B8504931A1.description:
Describe
changes in the
community as told
by an older relative
or friend.

C3281ACB9C4D434FA66A39F5E349B85A.description:
Engage with items of clothing from the past or “then”
(e.g., hats, coats, shoes).

088FA3F5CF3349C1873F7B056B521726.description:
Engage with representations of people wearing
clothing from earlier time periods or “then.”

74F2A667F1A449DF8D1586F955B3C8FF.description:
Match
pictures that
identify change as
now and then.

80F1A383180D44CE9EED8BB38EDF6429.description:
Show and
communicate about
personal pictures/
experiences over
time.

6A46E013315A45559526386C1FC4A22C.description:
Sort
pictures or objects
that identify events/
tools from past or
present.

A4148C7FDEEF4C3D8D2D78FF65DEE26D.description:
Primary and
secondary sources can be
used to show change over
time.

77F16D3CC9924897822E2D8B3F759784.description:
Engage with representations of a person/character
at three different ages (e.g., child, teenager, adult).

11449239976E48689C8ABAE7482E8BE0.description:
Discuss how events happen in order using a classroom
schedule or daily routine (using terms like first, next,
last).

C036B7B6F1B747508381B2BFEB50AEC2.description:
Identify
an event/activity
occurring before or
after another given
activity/event.

CF39E359431F43E88534D3498D75D487.description:
Place
a series of
three
personal events in
chronological order.

38251DD086EB4A7384FB37DA91B36D12.description:
Place
a sequence of
events or dates on
a timeline.

E18388CEF95C4D219975525645F4AE20.description:
Events in local history
can be shown on timelines
organized by years, decades
and centuries.
